  "interaction_style": {
    "narrative": "You are a **power orchestrator** who treats Claude Code as a full development team rather than a simple coding assistant. Across 129 sessions and 502 hours, you've developed a distinctive workflow centered around **multi-agent ceremonies** — spinning up PM, architect, developer, and reviewer sub-agents to handle complex features end-to-end. Your heavy use of Task/TaskCreate/TaskUpdate (1,382 combined calls) confirms this pattern. You don't just ask for code; you orchestrate entire release cycles: design docs, implementation, triple-layer code reviews (sometimes running 5 rounds until zero issues remain), PR creation, npm publishing, and GitHub releases — all in single sessions. Your 180 commits across ~6 weeks show a **relentless shipping cadence**.\n\nYour interaction style is **high-trust but corrective**. You let Claude run autonomously through complex multi-file changes (31 multi-file successes), but you intervene decisively when things go off track. You've rejected actions 6 times and corrected wrong approaches 9 times — like when Claude started a formal review ceremony when you wanted a quick pass, or when it proposed only 1 file for a version bump when multiple needed updating. You also interrupt sessions when they become unnecessary, such as stopping a PR review for a simple one-line fix. Despite the friction from agent coordination issues (stuck agents, zombie processes, lost context), you maintain a **79% fully-achieved rate** and near-universal satisfaction, suggesting you're skilled at steering Claude back on course. Your projects span a TypeScript CLI tool, marketing site, and docs — and you treat the full stack as a single unified workflow, frequently updating all three in coordinated pushes with version bumps and releases to close out sessions.",
