  "on_the_horizon": {
    "intro": "Your 129 sessions show a power user pushing Claude Code toward full autonomous orchestration — the friction patterns reveal exactly where to unlock the next level of agent-driven development.",
    "opportunities": [
      {
        "title": "Self-Healing Multi-Agent Review Pipelines",
        "whats_possible": "Your top friction points are agent coordination failures — stuck reviewers, lost context, zombie agents. You can build a resilient orchestration pattern where the lead agent monitors sub-agent health, auto-recovers stuck tasks, and guarantees all review outputs are captured and posted to GitHub before declaring completion. This eliminates the manual babysitting that interrupted at least 5 of your sessions.",
        "how_to_try": "Use Claude Code's Task/TaskCreate tools with explicit health-check loops and timeout-based fallback logic baked into your orchestration prompt.",
        "copyable_prompt": "You are a release orchestrator. For PR #[NUMBER]:\n\n1. Spawn 3 review agents: security-reviewer, logic-reviewer, style-reviewer\n2. After spawning each, set a 3-minute timeout. If any agent hasn't reported via TaskUpdate within that window, kill it and absorb its review scope into your own pass.\n3. Collect ALL findings into a single structured list. For each finding: file, line, severity (P0-P2), fix description.\n4. Apply all P0 and P1 fixes directly. For each fix, run the relevant test file via Bash.\n5. Post a consolidated review comment to the GitHub PR with all findings and fix statuses.\n6. Do NOT declare the review complete until: (a) all agents have reported or been absorbed, (b) all fixes are pushed, (c) the PR comment is confirmed posted.\n\nIf you hit a rate limit, wait 60 seconds and retry. If a sub-agent crashes, log it and continue. Never leave zombie agents running."
      },
      {
        "title": "Test-Driven Autonomous Feature Shipping",
        "whats_possible": "You had multiple sessions where tests broke after a PR was declared ready, or missing dependencies slipped through. An iterate-against-tests workflow can autonomously write failing tests first, implement until green, then run the full suite as a gate — catching issues like the jsonrepair dependency miss or the idempotency test break before you ever see them. This turns your 180 commits into higher-confidence releases.",
