## At a Glance

**What's working:** You've developed a genuinely sophisticated multi-agent orchestration workflow — running full dev ceremonies with PM, architect, dev, and reviewer roles to ship production-quality PRs. Your discipline of iterating code reviews until zero issues remain is uncommon and shows you're treating Claude as a real quality gate. You've also nailed end-to-end release automation, shipping numerous versioned releases entirely through Claude. See _Impressive Things You Did_.

**What's hindering you:** On Claude's side, it consistently misses obvious next steps in your workflows (not creating PRs, not posting review comments, not bumping all version files) until you explicitly ask — which is frustrating given how many times you've done this sequence. On your side, the multi-agent orchestration ceremonies frequently break down with stuck agents, lost context, and zombie reviewers, and the overhead of managing these failures likely costs more time than the ceremony saves on smaller tasks. See _Where Things Go Wrong_.

**Quick wins to try:** Try creating **custom slash commands** (`/release`, `/review-cycle`) that encode your standard workflow sequences — this directly solves the "Claude forgets the next step" problem without you having to repeat yourself. You could also set up **hooks** to auto-run your test suite after edits, catching broken tests before PRs are declared ready instead of after. See _Features to Try_.

**Ambitious workflows:** As models get more capable, your multi-agent review pipelines should become self-healing — the orchestrator will reliably monitor sub-agent health, auto-recover stuck tasks, and guarantee outputs are posted without your intervention. Even more exciting: a single-prompt release pipeline that spawns parallel agents for version bumps, docs sync, changelog generation, and dependency verification, all converging at publish — compressing what currently takes multiple sessions into one autonomous run. See _On the Horizon_.

